Parallelizing a neural network typically involves splitting the data into smaller subsets and processing each subset in parallel on different computers or GPUs. There are several ways to achieve this:

1. Data Parallelism: This involves splitting the data into subsets and training each subset on a separate GPU. The model weights are then synchronized after training.
2. Model Parallelism: This involves breaking down the network into smaller components that can be trained in parallel on different GPUs.
3. Tensor Parallelism: This involves processing the tensors in parallel across multiple GPUs. This can be done by using DataParallel or ModelParallel in TensorFlow or Theano.

It is important to note that not all neural networks can be parallelized efficiently. Splitting the data or the network may result in a decrease in performance if the subsets are too small or the hardware is not powerful enough. It is also important to ensure that the data and model are properly synchronized after training to avoid errors. Parallelizing a neural network requires careful attention to the hardware and software configuration, as well as knowledge of the specific neural network architecture and training algorithm. It is recommended to consult with experts in deep learning and hardware acceleration to achieve optimal parallelization
